You need to account for the case where the jiraissue.issuestatus is null.

We had quite a large number of these - and in all cases, the worflow status was ok - so it was just a matter of updating jiraissue with the value from OS_WFENTRY 

REPORT:
{code:SQL}
SELECT     jiraissue.pkey, OS_WFENTRY.STATE, jiraissue.issuestatus
FROM         jiraissue INNER JOIN
                      OS_WFENTRY ON jiraissue.WORKFLOW_ID = OS_WFENTRY.ID
WHERE     (jiraissue.issuestatus IS NULL)
ORDER BY jiraissue.pkey;
{code}

FIX:
{code:SQL}
update jiraissue
set    issuestatus = ( select state 
                       from   os_wfentry
                       where  id = workflow_id )
where  issuestatus is null;
{code}

And pls make it efficient (no N+1 database calls...) - the other integrity checks are quite slow because of inefficient database access...

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Server*. Using *JIRA Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRACLOUD-7408].
  {panel}

My users keep requesting a feature where they can be added to the watch list for certain issues. Building a custom jsp page that adds them as a watcher to a set of issues isn't hard but requires too much maintenance.

As far as I know a reporting portlet would not be sufficient - basically this feature would work as a filter subscription, where they user could set a check box to 'auto watch' every issue the filter finds.

